President Obama and President Yanukovych have reaffirmed the strategic partnership between Ukraine and the United States and their commitment to realizing its full potential. They discussed common interests and shared values, including democracy, economic freedom, security, and energy security. President Yanukovych expressed his commitment to addressing Ukraine's economic challenges through reforms and cooperation with the IMF, which President Obama supports. They also discussed increasing bilateral trade and investment. The two leaders share a vision of a world without nuclear weapons and pledged to work together to prevent proliferation. President Yanukovych announced Ukraine's decision to eliminate all highly-enriched uranium stocks, with the United States providing technical and financial assistance. They agreed to strengthen cooperation in the peaceful uses of atomic energy and nuclear safety. The United States has contributed significant funds to restore the Chornobyl nuclear reactor site and reaffirms its commitment to supporting Ukraine in this effort.